{"cursor":"27470","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"[[File:World map of Male Obesity, 2008.svg|thumb|300px|World obesity prevalence\namong males. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n]]\n\n[[File:World map of Female Obesity, 2008.svg|thumb|300px|World obesity\nprevalence among females. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n]] member countries in the years 1996â2003. ]] For\nthousands of years obesity was rarely seen. It was\nnot until the 20th century that it became common, so much so that in 1997 the\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) formally recognized obesity as a global\nepidemic. As of 2005 the WHO estimates that at least\n400 million adults (9.8%) are obese, with higher rates among women than men.\n\nAs of 2008, The World Health Organization claimed that 1.5 billion adults, 20\nand older, were overweight and of these over 200 million men and nearly 300\nmillion women were obese. The rate of\nobesity also increases with age at least up to 50 or 60 years old.\n\nOnce considered a problem only of high-income countries, obesity rates are\nrising worldwide. These increases have been felt most dramatically in urban\nsettings. The only remaining region of the world where\nobesity is not common is sub-Saharan Africa.\n","linknr":802,"url":"Obesity_epidemic","recorded":1362505235,"links":47,"instances":["website"],"pdf":["http://www.iotf.org/database/documents/GlobalPrevalenceofAdultObesity16thDecember08.pdf","http://www.iotf.org/database/documents/GlobalPrevalenceofAdultObesity16thDecember08.pdf","http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_894_(part1).pdf","http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_894_(part1).pdf","http://www.fao.org/statistics/compendium_2006/pdf/CPR_ESS_E.pdf","http://www.fao.org/statistics/compendium_2006/pdf/CPR_ESS_E.pdf","http://www.who.int/dietphysicalactivity/media/en/gsfs_obesity.pdf","http://www.who.int/dietphysicalactivity/media/en/gsfs_obesity.pdf","http://www.iussp.org/Bangkok2002/S7Agrawal.pdf","http://www.iussp.org/Bangkok2002/S7Agrawal.pdf","http://e